      text=""" [ANS] Elara’s life was a carefully curated collection of quiet moments. As a rare book restorer, her days were spent in the hushed company of brittle paper and faded ink, mending the histories of others while her own remained deliberately uneventful. Her small apartment, filled with the scent of old leather and brewing tea, was a sanctuary from a world she found too loud, too unpredictable. She preferred the predictable rhythm of her work, the familiar faces at the local market, and the comforting weight of a book in her lap each evening. Surprises were unwelcome guests, and she had built walls of routine high enough to keep them out.

